-- 
Taiwan Stocks: Acer, Chinatrust Financial, Compal, Polaris

-- B y   A d e l a   L i n
-- 
2011-03-29T06:14:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-29/cathay-chinatrust-compal-mega-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Stocks of the following companies
had unusual moves in  Taiwan  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 1:30 p.m. close in Taipei.  The Taiex Index rose 43.51, or 0.5 percent, to 8,596.57.  Acer Inc. (2353)  (2353 TT), the world’s second-biggest personal
computer maker, tumbled 6.9 percent to NT$63.1, the lowest close
since July 14, 2009, after Goldman Sachs Group Inc. cut the
stock’s rating to “sell” from “neutral,” saying that the
company’s growth model appears “challenged.” The stock has
lost 13 percent in two days, the most since September 2008.  The brokerage reduced its share-price forecast to NT$48
from NT$80, analyst Henry King wrote in a report.  China Development Financial Holding Corp. (2883)  (2883 TT) rose 4
percent to NT$11.70 after the financial holding company said
that it was interested in a “close relationship” with Polaris
Securities Co. (2854 TT). Polaris Securities climbed 4 percent
NT$19.65 after the company said its chairman Lin Hsiao-ta
received a letter of intent on a possible merger from China
Development Financial.  Chinatrust Financial Holding Co. (2891 TT), Taiwan’s
biggest credit-card issuer, gained 0.2 percent to NT$24.65.
Chinatrust agreed to pay $180 million for the Taiwan business of
MetLife Inc.  Compal Electronics Inc. (2324)  (2324 TT) dropped 2.6 percent to
NT$30, the lowest since Aug. 21, 2009, after BNP Paribas cut the
stock’s rating to “hold” from “buy,” saying the company will
be affected by the “weak” sales and shipment forecasts from
its client, Acer.  The brokerage reduced Compal’s share-price forecast to
NT$33 from NT$44, analysts led by Patty Liu wrote in a report.  To contact the reporter on this story:
